  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>Fagor Industrial vs Fagor Electrodomésticos — fact-accuracy disambig</h2>
    <p>The most important single fact for anyone calling about Fagor service: there are two different companies that share the Fagor name, and only one is relevant to commercial laundry repair.</p>
    <p><b>Fagor Electrodomésticos</b> was the residential appliance company — home refrigerators, dishwashers, washing machines, cooktops for the Spanish and European consumer market. That company went bankrupt in 2013 during the Spanish financial crisis and was subsequently acquired by Brandt, a French appliance manufacturer. The residential Fagor home-appliance line no longer exists as an active Spanish manufacturer — parts availability for pre-2013 residential Fagor equipment is limited and inconsistent.</p>
    <p><b>Fagor Industrial</b> — the commercial + industrial equipment company serving restaurants, commercial laundry, and industrial food-service — survived the 2013 crisis independently. It continues operating as a division of Onnera Group, based in Oñati in the Basque Country of Spain, and remains an active manufacturer with ongoing production, parts chain, and dealer network. Fagor Industrial is what our commercial laundry coverage addresses. The two companies share the Fagor name but are independent entities with different parts, different engineering, and different availability; parts from one don't fit the other.</p>
    <p>Onnera Group itself is part of the Mondragón Cooperative heritage — the largest worker-owned cooperative federation in the world, founded in Spain's Basque Country in 1956. Mondragón structure means engineering decisions are internally directed by worker-owners rather than shaped by private-equity or conglomerate integration. Similar operational character to Alliance Laundry Systems' ESOP structure (also employee-owned).</p>
  </div></section>

